    Qu Chun, whose courtesy name was Zihou, traced his lineage to the western lands of Long. His ancestor ninety generations back was Mou, who aided the Lord of Millet in feeding the multitudes and earned great merit—this is he whom the Book of Songs celebrates, saying, 'He grants us millet and barley.' Mou first withdrew from the world, refusing office, declaring: 'I shall eat only what my own hands have tilled.' So he dwelt in the fields. When word reached the court of his worthy descendants, an imperial edict was issued to summon him in a cushioned carriage. The command passed through the prefectures and counties, each instructing their magistrates to send him off with great honor. A minister was dispatched to visit his humble dwelling in person, and there between mortar and pestle, a bond of friendship was forged. Light harmonized with shadow, refinement mingled with dust, and through the gradual steeping and fermentation, a subtle elegance emerged. Mou then rejoiced, saying: 'It is friendship that perfects us'—and truly, was this not so? Word of his virtuous character spread abroad, and a memorial arch was erected at his gate. Following the court to sacrifice at the Circular Mound, he was enfeoffed as Marquis of Zhongshan, granted ten thousand households and five thousand sealed households, and his clan was renamed the Qu family.

    Five generations later, his descendant aided the King of Cheng, bearing the burden of state and altar, and brought about an era of great peace and flourishing abundance. When the King of Kang ascended the throne, the family gradually fell into disfavor and was placed under interdiction, their names inscribed in imperial edicts. Thus no distinguished members appeared thereafter, and they concealed themselves among the common people. In the early Wei, Chun's father Zhuo became known to the world. Working alongside the Secretariat Official Xu Mei, he was gradually elevated to prominence at court, with Zhuo never absent from discussion. Then one day an informant reported to the emperor that Mei had formed a private alliance with Zhuo, gradually encouraging disorder. The emperor raged and summoned Mei for interrogation. Mei kowtowed in apology: 'My association with Zhuo stems from his possession of a sage's virtue; I simply partake of it from time to time.' The emperor rebuked him. Later, when the Jin received the mandate of heaven, knowing that chaos would follow, Zhuo harbored no ambition for office. He joined Liu Ling and Ruan Ji and their company for gatherings in the bamboo grove, thus spending his remaining days.

    Chun possessed a broad and profound character, vast and flowing like ten thousand acres of water. Whether cleared or disturbed, it remained neither transparent nor turbid. His manner captivated the age, and he seemed to enhance the spirit of all around him. He once visited the monk Ye for a day-long discourse, and the entire assembly dissolved into laughter. Thus he became known as the Recluse Qu, celebrated far and wide. From ministers and generals to shamans and physicians, from servants and herders to barbarians and foreigners—all who tasted the fragrance of his name cherished him. At every grand gathering, should the Recluse Qu fail to appear, all would fall silent, lamenting: 'Without the Recluse Qu, there is no joy.' Such was his esteem.

    The Grand Commandant Shan Tao, a man of discernment, once remarked of him: 'What fortunate crone bore such a wondrous child! Yet perhaps it is this very man who shall lead the realm astray.' The Public Bureau summoned him as Adjutant of Qingzhou, but deeming the position beneath his station, transferred him instead to Overseer of Pingyuan. After some time, he sighed: 'I shall not bend my waist for five measures of rice before provincial upstarts. Rather, I shall stand between wine jar and cutting board, engaging in worthy discourse.' A skilled physiognomist told him: 'Purple vapor surrounds your face; you are destined for great honors and a thousand measures of prosperity. Wait for the right opportunity and sell yourself dearly.'

    During the reign of the Later Chen emperor, he was appointed as an Assistant Official of Guest Relations through his status as a man of good family. The emperor was moved by his bearing and intended greater use of him. He was thus marked with the seal of a golden bowl and rapidly advanced to Grand Master of Light and Master of Ceremonial Receptions, elevated in rank to Duke. Whenever the emperor and ministers held council, the emperor would have Chun moderate their discourse. His judgments and responses were measured and pleasing. The emperor deeply approved, saying: 'You embody straightness itself, you alone are clear—you unlock my heart and refresh my spirit.' Gaining power and responsibility, Chun excelled in befriending the virtuous and receiving guests, in providing for the elderly and dispensing wine and meat, in making offerings to spirits and sacrificing to ancestral temples. Even at private evening banquets, only Chun and the palace attendants were permitted to serve, while even close ministers were excluded. From then on, as the emperor indulged in drinking and neglected affairs of state, Chun sealed his own lips and dared not speak. Thus the scholars of propriety regarded him as an enemy. Yet the emperor continually protected him. Chun was also fond of accumulating wealth and building estates, which earned him the scorn of contemporary opinion.

    When the emperor asked, 'What is your particular weakness?' Chun replied: 'In ancient times, Du Yu was obsessed with the Commentary, Wang Ji with horses, and I with coins.' The emperor laughed heartily and grew yet fonder of him. Once when Chun presented a petition before the throne, the emperor, noting his foul breath, said with distaste: 'You grow old and weak—are you unfit for my service?' Chun immediately removed his cap and apologized: 'If your servant accepts rank without restraint, he risks sudden ruin. I beg to retire to my private estate, where I might learn the measure of sufficiency.' The emperor commanded his attendants to support him out. Upon returning home, Chun fell suddenly ill and died that very night. He left no sons, but his younger kinsman Qing later served the Tang dynasty, rising to the rank of Inner Court Official, and his descendants flourished again in the Middle Kingdom.

    The Historian remarks: 'The ancestors of the Qu family conferred benefits upon the people and passed down virtue to their descendants, their fragrant merit reaching heaven itself—truly they possessed the bearing of worthy forebears. Yet Chun, though possessed of subtle wisdom, rose from humble circumstances and was early selected for high station, and stood between wine jar and cutting board. Yet he could not distinguish right from wrong, could not steady the tottering kingdom, and ultimately became the laughingstock of the realm. In this, the words of the Grand Commandant ring true indeed.'
  footnotes:
    - The 'Lord of Millet' (Houji) is a legendary culture hero in Chinese mythology credited with teaching agriculture.
    - The reference to 'harmony of light and shadow, mingling with dust' alludes to Daoist philosophy, particularly Laozi's concept of blending with the mundane world.
    - The 'Circular Mound' (Yuanqiu) refers to the ritual ground where emperors performed sacrifices to heaven.
    - The 'bamboo grove' gatherings reference the Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove (Zhulin Qixian), a group of fourth-century poets and philosophers known for their reclusive lifestyle and philosophical discussions.
    - The 'golden bowl' (jin'ou) is a metaphor for imperial selection and favor.
    - The final critique by the Historian employs the traditional historiographical technique of moral judgment, emphasizing how Chun's failure to provide moral counsel to a dissolute ruler represents a betrayal of intellectual responsibility.
